**Problem Description**
The recommit mechanism in op-geth fails to work properly, causing blocks to contain only 1 transaction (coinbase) instead of processing transactions from the pool. This results in severely degraded transaction throughput.
**Root Cause**: The payload.interrupt atomic variable is shared across multiple payload building cycles within the same Payload object. Once the Consensus Layer calls payload.resolve() and sets the interrupt signal to commitInterruptResolve (4), all subsequent recommit update builds immediately abort in commitTransactions() without processing any transactions.

**Current Behavior**
```
// First build - works fine
commitTransactions start currentTxCount=1 initialInterruptSignal=0
// ... processes transactions normally

// CL calls resolve(), sets interrupt=4

// Recommit update build - immediately fails
commitTransactions start currentTxCount=1 initialInterruptSignal=4
commitTransactions interrupted signal=4 processedTxs=0
```

**Expected Behavior**
Recommit updates should be able to process transactions from the pool, not immediately abort due to stale interrupt signals from previous resolve calls.

**Solution**
Reset resolve interrupt signals at the beginning of each generateWork call to allow recommit mechanism to function properly.
**File**: `miner/worker.go`
**Function**: `generateWork`
Add interrupt signal reset logic before `fillTransactions`:
```
// Smart interrupt signal handling
interrupt := genParam.interrupt
if interrupt == nil {
    interrupt = new(atomic.Int32)
} else {
    // Reset resolve interrupt at the start of all builds
    currentSignal := interrupt.Load()
    if currentSignal == commitInterruptResolve {
        // Reset resolve interrupt to allow build to continue
        interrupt.Store(commitInterruptNone)
        log.Info("Reset resolve interrupt for new build", "oldSignal", currentSignal, "isUpdate", genParam.isUpdate)
    }
    // For update builds, also reset any non-None signal to prevent delayed interrupts
    if genParam.isUpdate && currentSignal != commitInterruptNone {
        interrupt.Store(commitInterruptNone)
        log.Info("Reset interrupt for update build", "oldSignal", currentSignal)
    }
}
```

**Impact**
Fixes recommit mechanism: Update builds can now process transactions instead of immediately aborting
Improves transaction throughput: Blocks can include transactions from the pool via recommit updates
Maintains safety: Other interrupt types (timeout, new head) still work as expected
Backward compatible: No changes to external APIs or behavior

